And it’s state laws that matter the most, anyway.
Constitutional limits on federal authority aren’t erased during times of emergency.
Congress overrode President Nixon’s veto of the War Powers Resolution in 1973 and later zeroed out funding for the Vietnam War—effectively ending that conflict.
And the coronavirus epidemic is proof of the Founders’ wisdom.
Nor does the Defense Production Act allow the president power to revoke state emergency declarations; it expressly does not apply to employment, for one thing.